Opportunity -- tChapter Eighteen. Disappeared People // Law & Disorder -- tPart Three Fiction -- tChapter Nineteen. My Fiction Seems a Bit Inconsequential to Me Now // Treme’s Truth Claim -- tChapter Twenty. In the David Simon Business // Treme’s Mode of Production -- tChapter Twenty-one. The Continuance of Culture -- tChapter Twenty-two. All These Trucks Got Bodies? // Dramatizing Injustice -- tConclusion. Desitively Katrina -- tBibliography -- tFilms and Media -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAnyone who was not in New Orleans during Hurricane Katrina and the subsequent flooding of the city experienced the disaster as a media event, a flood of images pouring across television and computer screens. The twenty-four-hour news cycle created a surplus of representation that overwhelmed viewers and complicated understandings of the storm, the flood, and the aftermath. As time passed, documentary and fictional filmmakers took up the challenge of explaining what had happened in New Orleans, reaching beyond news reports to portray the lived experiences of survivors of Katrina. But while these narratives presented alternative understandings and more opportunities for empathy than TV news, Katrina remained a mediated experience. In Flood of Images, Bernie Cook offers the most in-depth, wide-ranging, and carefully argued analysis of the mediation and meanings of Katrina. He engages in innovative, close, and comparative visual readings of news coverage on CNN, Fox News, and NBC; documentaries including Spike Lee’s When the Levees Broke and If God Is Willing and Da Creek Don’t Rise, Tia Lessin and Carl Deal’s Trouble the Water, and Dawn Logsdon and Lolis Elie’s Faubourg Treme; and the HBO drama Treme. Cook examines the production practices that shaped Katrina-as-media-event, exploring how those choices structured the possible memories and meanings of Katrina and how the media’s memory-making has been contested. In Flood of Images, Cook intervenes in the ongoing process of remembering and understanding Katrina.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Okt 2021) 0aHurricane Katrina, 2005xPress coverage. 0aHurricane Katrina, 2005xSocial aspects. 0aMass mediaxObjectivityzUnited States. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Television / History & Criticism.2bisacsh40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292771352423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292771352/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MUAR  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK